WEBVTT

00:05.506 --> 00:07.925
<i>‐ Tonight,</i>
<i>we celebrate Veteran's Day...</i>

00:07.925 --> 00:10.177
‐ This hammer belonged
to my grandfather

00:10.177 --> 00:12.179
who served in World War II.

00:12.179 --> 00:15.515
<i>‐ With the biggest reveal</i>
<i>in "Forged in Fire" history.</i>

00:15.515 --> 00:17.184
<i>Four smiths</i>
<i>will pay tribute</i>

00:17.184 --> 00:19.061
<i>to the men and women</i>
<i>who served</i>

00:19.061 --> 00:21.188
<i>by embarking on a series</i>
<i>of military‐themed challenges</i>

00:21.188 --> 00:22.523
<i>unlike any other.</i>

00:22.523 --> 00:24.316
‐ I never quit.
Ever!

00:24.316 --> 00:26.652
<i>‐ Which smith</i>
<i>will adapt and overcome</i>

00:26.652 --> 00:30.697
<i>to earn $10,000 and the rank</i>
<i>of "Forged in Fire" champion?</i>

00:30.697 --> 00:33.408
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:33.408 --> 00:36.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:36.703 --> 00:38.872
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

00:38.872 --> 00:41.041
<i>‐ My name is Billy Salyers,</i>

00:41.041 --> 00:42.709
<i>and I'm from Rutherfordton,</i>
<i>North Carolina.</i>

00:42.709 --> 00:45.420
For me, bladesmithing
is all about

00:45.420 --> 00:47.673
sharing life and sharing faith.

00:47.673 --> 00:49.550
<i>The most important thing</i>
<i>isn't the blade,</i>

00:49.550 --> 00:52.594
it's the hand that wields it,
and every blade that I make

00:52.594 --> 00:54.638
<i>is a chance to connect</i>
<i>with somebody else.</i>

00:54.638 --> 00:58.809
<i>‐ My name is Robert Soria and</i>
<i>I own Rhino Ironworx forge.</i>

00:58.809 --> 01:02.729
Rhino comes from a book
that I read and it all involves

01:02.729 --> 01:04.523
<i>seeing a goal</i>
<i>that's in front of you</i>

01:04.523 --> 01:06.900
<i>and charging at it</i>
<i>with everything you've got.</i>

01:06.900 --> 01:10.404
What can stop a charging rhino?
Absolutely nothing.

01:10.404 --> 01:13.073
<i>‐ My name is Mike Johnston.</i>

01:13.073 --> 01:15.117
Before I got into
bladesmithing,

01:15.117 --> 01:17.578
I was a police officer
for 30 years.

01:17.578 --> 01:19.788
<i>I think the most important</i>
<i>lesson that I learned</i>

01:19.788 --> 01:21.957
<i>from my former career</i>
<i>in law enforcement</i>

01:21.957 --> 01:24.501
is you just don't ever quit.

01:24.501 --> 01:25.919
It's never an option.

01:25.919 --> 01:28.297
<i>‐ My name is</i>
<i>Shawn Chakravarty.</i>

01:28.297 --> 01:29.923
<i>I'm from Phoenix, Arizona.</i>

01:29.923 --> 01:32.259
I'm a full‐time
cybersecurity professional.

01:32.259 --> 01:34.219
<i>Working in cybersecurity,</i>

01:34.219 --> 01:36.263
<i>you're facing</i>
<i>a never‐ending battle.</i>

01:36.263 --> 01:38.849
Having a balance
like bladesmithing,

01:38.849 --> 01:40.976
that you can hold something
that you made

01:40.976 --> 01:42.519
at the end of the day,

01:42.519 --> 01:45.230
<i>is paramount</i>
<i>to maintaining sanity.</i>

01:45.230 --> 01:49.860
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:49.860 --> 01:52.029
‐ Sup?
‐ How's it goin'?

01:52.029 --> 01:54.781
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:54.781 --> 01:56.366
You are here to engage
in three rounds

01:56.366 --> 01:58.327
of timed
edged weapon‐making competition

01:58.327 --> 01:59.661
designed to test every aspect

01:59.661 --> 02:01.246
of your bladesmithing
capabilities

02:01.246 --> 02:02.998
in front of a panel
of expert judges

02:02.998 --> 02:05.042
who will tell us
which of you

02:05.042 --> 02:06.793
is the next
"Forged in Fire" champion

02:06.793 --> 02:10.130
leaving here
with a check for $10,000.

02:10.130 --> 02:12.174
Let's meet your judges now.

02:12.174 --> 02:15.677
First, ABS Master Smith,
J. Neilson.

02:15.677 --> 02:18.055
Next, Historic Weapons
Re‐creation Specialist,

02:18.055 --> 02:19.306
David Baker.

02:19.306 --> 02:21.850
And Doug.

02:21.850 --> 02:23.393
Bladesmiths...

02:23.393 --> 02:25.354
on this Veteran's Day
we're commemorating

02:25.354 --> 02:27.939
every American service member
who has served this country

02:27.939 --> 02:30.108
by having you guys
forge signature blades

02:30.108 --> 02:32.653
in your signature style
from this.

02:32.653 --> 02:35.447
<i>[rock music]</i>

02:35.447 --> 02:37.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:37.491 --> 02:40.702
<i>‐ Great.</i>
<i>It's a tank.</i>

02:40.702 --> 02:44.915
<i>And the barrel</i>
<i>is pointing right at me.</i>

02:44.915 --> 02:46.708
Is that thing loaded,
or what?

02:46.708 --> 02:50.754
‐ Gentlemen, this is
a World War II Panzer tank.

02:50.754 --> 02:53.507
It's made out of high‐carbon
and mild steel

02:53.507 --> 02:56.009
and your challenge
is to harvest the steel

02:56.009 --> 02:58.178
that you need,
mild and high carbon,

02:58.178 --> 03:01.181
<i>to make a San Mai blade</i>

03:01.181 --> 03:04.184
<i>between 12 and 14 inches</i>
<i>in length.</i>

03:04.184 --> 03:06.269
<i>‐ I don't know</i>
<i>where I'm gonna harvest from.</i>

03:06.269 --> 03:08.605
<i>I don't know how</i>
<i>I'm going to find</i>

03:08.605 --> 03:11.942
hardenable steel
to make a blade.

03:11.942 --> 03:13.402
‐ You'll have three hours

03:13.402 --> 03:15.195
in which
to complete this challenge.

03:15.195 --> 03:17.531
If you make it to round two,
you'll have an opportunity

03:17.531 --> 03:19.282
to attach handles
to those blades

03:19.282 --> 03:21.493
so we can test them
for strength and durability

03:21.493 --> 03:23.620
in a German helmet strike

03:23.620 --> 03:27.833
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

03:27.833 --> 03:29.543
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:29.543 --> 03:31.545
Your three hours starts...

03:31.545 --> 03:32.796
now.

03:32.796 --> 03:35.715
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:35.715 --> 03:37.175
What do you guys think
of this challenge?

03:37.175 --> 03:39.177
We've got this Panzer tank.

03:39.177 --> 03:41.221
‐ This is great for what we're
trying to celebrate here.

03:41.221 --> 03:42.806
‐ It's certainly got
an abundance of steel

03:42.806 --> 03:44.391
to choose from.
[chuckles]

03:44.391 --> 03:46.601
‐ These down low,
drop 'em off and cut 'em.

03:46.601 --> 03:49.312
<i>‐ Obviously,</i>
<i>the big metal glaring thing</i>

03:49.312 --> 03:50.772
<i>are the tracks of this.</i>

03:50.772 --> 03:51.773
<i>What type of steel is it?</i>

03:51.773 --> 03:53.316
‐ It's a mild steel,

03:53.316 --> 03:55.110
probably hardenable
to a certain point.

03:55.110 --> 03:57.571
‐ I'd be looking for
the high‐carbon steel first.

03:57.571 --> 03:58.947
That's going to be
a real challenge.

03:58.947 --> 04:00.532
‐ I'll help you
over here with this.

04:00.532 --> 04:02.409
‐ You can if you want.
‐ Yep, let's do it.

04:02.409 --> 04:04.744
‐ We break off into teams and
it just seems totally fluid.

04:04.744 --> 04:06.997
<i>Mike and I</i>
<i>head to the back of the tank</i>

04:06.997 --> 04:09.583
going and looking
for the handles.

04:09.583 --> 04:12.878
<i>We're assuming that those</i>
<i>have to be high carbon steel.</i>

04:12.878 --> 04:15.088
‐ I'm going to look
at the sparks.

04:15.088 --> 04:16.923
<i>The sparks give you</i>
<i>an indication</i>

04:16.923 --> 04:19.593
<i>of what the steel is made of.</i>

04:19.593 --> 04:21.303
‐ That's the nice thing
about starting out

04:21.303 --> 04:23.597
with that angle grinder
and cutting that steel,

04:23.597 --> 04:26.266
is you can see those sparks
are complex sparks.

04:26.266 --> 04:28.935
That's already telling you
it's high carbon steel.

04:28.935 --> 04:29.936
[metallic clank]

04:29.936 --> 04:31.396
‐ Maybe here or here?

04:31.396 --> 04:33.482
<i>‐ My first thing goes to,</i>

04:33.482 --> 04:35.567
"I need to harvest
some mild steel."

04:35.567 --> 04:37.110
<i>The tank treads are good</i>

04:37.110 --> 04:38.695
<i>because they're</i>
<i>one of those things</i>

04:38.695 --> 04:41.740
that are made to be able
to swap out pretty easily.

04:41.740 --> 04:43.116
They want to them to be

04:43.116 --> 04:45.452
as relatively inexpensive
as they can.

04:45.452 --> 04:47.245
I mean, it's a tank tread.

04:47.245 --> 04:48.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:48.997 --> 04:50.832
‐ Now, these guys
are doing great teamwork.

04:50.832 --> 04:52.626
We've got two guys
cuttin' hard carbon,

04:52.626 --> 04:54.252
two guys cuttin' low carbon.

04:54.252 --> 04:56.463
Get this harvesting done.

04:56.463 --> 04:58.298
‐ We're almost through it.

04:58.298 --> 05:00.550
‐ This is
unbelievably challenging.

05:00.550 --> 05:02.219
Oh, my goodness.

05:02.219 --> 05:04.638
These tank treads
are, like, this thick,

05:04.638 --> 05:06.139
and they're bolted on,

05:06.139 --> 05:07.808
and I'm trying
to cut these things

05:07.808 --> 05:09.976
<i>with the acetylene torch.</i>

05:09.976 --> 05:11.394
‐ How many more we need?

05:11.394 --> 05:12.979
‐ One more,
this one right here.

05:12.979 --> 05:14.856
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:14.856 --> 05:17.359
San Mai means‐‐
both: three layers.

05:17.359 --> 05:19.861
These guys actually
have to forge out

05:19.861 --> 05:22.989
the three different sections
of steel to make them even,

05:22.989 --> 05:26.827
weld those together,
and then forge‐weld them

05:26.827 --> 05:29.037
so that the high carbon
is on the inside

05:29.037 --> 05:31.414
layered in between
two sections of mild steel.

05:31.414 --> 05:32.999
‐ And in between that,

05:32.999 --> 05:35.126
you've got to make sure
everything's clean.

05:35.126 --> 05:36.837
<i>‐ So there's actually</i>
<i>a few different approaches</i>

05:36.837 --> 05:38.672
<i>to San Mai.</i>

05:38.672 --> 05:41.591
<i>Roll this mild steel around</i>
<i>into the shape of a taco</i>

05:41.591 --> 05:44.219
<i>and you place the carbon steel</i>
<i>in between.</i>

05:44.219 --> 05:46.054
<i>Then you've got</i>
<i>the sandwich shape.</i>

05:46.054 --> 05:48.723
<i>I decide to go</i>
<i>with the sandwich style.</i>

05:48.723 --> 05:50.976
I think it's more reliable.

05:50.976 --> 05:53.520
‐ Shawn stretched out
his high carbon steel,

05:53.520 --> 05:56.106
but he still has to
stretch out that tank tread,

05:56.106 --> 05:58.316
clean that
to get a clean weld.

05:58.316 --> 06:01.444
<i>‐ I know that forge welding,</i>
<i>more than anything else,</i>

06:01.444 --> 06:03.613
is successful
when you have clean steel.

06:03.613 --> 06:05.782
<i>If I don't clean up</i>
<i>this steel,</i>

06:05.782 --> 06:07.367
<i>I'm looking at delaminations.</i>

06:07.367 --> 06:09.870
I'm looking at my piece
just falling apart,

06:09.870 --> 06:12.706
<i>so I'm gonna take my time.</i>

06:13.874 --> 06:16.293
‐ All right, let's see.

06:16.293 --> 06:20.255
<i>Mike and Shawn cut the high</i>
<i>carbon bars for all of us.</i>

06:20.255 --> 06:22.674
I throw that in the forge
so that I can get it heating up

06:22.674 --> 06:24.885
and start working on
shaping these mild steel pieces

06:24.885 --> 06:26.428
to put my San Mai together.

06:26.428 --> 06:27.929
I'm getting 'em
nice and clean

06:27.929 --> 06:30.098
so that way I can
forge weld them to the sides

06:30.098 --> 06:32.267
once I've flattened out
my hardenable steel.

06:32.267 --> 06:34.269
I want to make
a sandwich out of it,

06:34.269 --> 06:36.021
one layer on top of the other,

06:36.021 --> 06:38.857
with my good hardenable steel
right in the middle.

06:38.857 --> 06:41.735
‐ Sections of those tracks
are really gnarly.

06:41.735 --> 06:44.529
With San Mai,
when you put all these metals,

06:44.529 --> 06:45.822
you're going to get
a lot of inclusions

06:45.822 --> 06:47.407
if you don't clean it.

06:47.407 --> 06:48.742
‐ This challenge
is nerve‐wracking.

06:48.742 --> 06:50.327
I can win, I can lose,

06:50.327 --> 06:52.746
but honestly,
we're celebrating our veterans.

06:52.746 --> 06:54.456
‐ One hour has elapsed!

06:54.456 --> 06:57.917
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work!

06:57.917 --> 06:59.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:59.419 --> 07:03.131
‐ This is my first attempt
at San Mai,

07:03.131 --> 07:07.177
and I decide
to use a sandwich technique.

07:07.177 --> 07:09.929
‐ Mike's gonna be
chasing issues.

07:09.929 --> 07:11.723
‐ Mike hasn't cleaned
any of that material.

07:11.723 --> 07:15.977
‐ I don't take quite as much
time as I should

07:15.977 --> 07:17.812
cleaning up my steel,

07:17.812 --> 07:20.649
<i>and this could really cause me</i>
<i>problems down the road,</i>

07:20.649 --> 07:23.526
but I know
I'm under a real time crunch.

07:23.526 --> 07:25.278
The clock is running,

07:25.278 --> 07:29.532
so I do clean the rust
off of the mild steel

07:29.532 --> 07:31.493
<i>and keep moving on.</i>

07:31.493 --> 07:33.703
‐ There's forge scale
on everything he's got,

07:33.703 --> 07:36.373
and he's going to cook it
together.

07:36.373 --> 07:40.627
‐ My father made knives
in World War II.

07:40.627 --> 07:43.463
He was shot down
on a bombing mission

07:43.463 --> 07:47.175
<i>and was taken</i>
<i>by the Dutch underground</i>

07:47.175 --> 07:48.927
<i>and while he was hiding out,</i>

07:48.927 --> 07:51.304
he made knives
for some of his flight crew.

07:52.889 --> 07:54.974
<i>I never made knives</i>
<i>with my father</i>

07:54.974 --> 07:57.310
so it's great
to honor the veterans

07:57.310 --> 07:59.562
and my father
in this competition.

07:59.562 --> 08:02.732
‐ I'm cleaning off
my mild steel.

08:02.732 --> 08:04.693
[bleep].

08:04.693 --> 08:06.986
<i>And I step in front of where</i>
<i>the sparks are coming out</i>

08:06.986 --> 08:09.531
<i>and I didn't have an apron on,</i>

08:09.531 --> 08:12.367
<i>so now the world</i>
<i>gets to see my belly.</i>

08:12.367 --> 08:14.077
[chuckles]

08:14.077 --> 08:15.829
‐ Looks like Robert
got in knife fight with Doug.

08:15.829 --> 08:16.913
You out there sparring
with Robert?

08:16.913 --> 08:18.289
‐ [laughs]

08:18.289 --> 08:19.833
‐ Thankfully
I brought an extra shirt

08:19.833 --> 08:21.167
so as soon as we're done
with this round

08:21.167 --> 08:22.335
I'm gonna go and change.

08:22.335 --> 08:24.379
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:24.379 --> 08:27.298
<i>I'm very excited to be able</i>
<i>to build a San Mai knife.</i>

08:27.298 --> 08:29.843
I've done it
several times before.

08:29.843 --> 08:33.012
‐ He's stretched out that steel
on big blue quite thin‐‐

08:33.012 --> 08:34.764
‐ Right.

08:34.764 --> 08:36.850
‐ So he needs to get
some thickness in that blade.

08:36.850 --> 08:38.935
<i>‐ Whatever application your</i>
<i>knife is going to be used for,</i>

08:38.935 --> 08:40.770
you have to be thinking
of that.

08:40.770 --> 08:43.356
<i>They put these knives through</i>
<i>a lifetime of punishment</i>

08:43.356 --> 08:45.233
so you have to be prepared.

08:45.233 --> 08:47.402
You have to be thinking
about that all the time.

08:47.402 --> 08:49.529
‐ Hot metal!

08:49.529 --> 08:51.656
‐ Billy, he's
brought that billet

08:51.656 --> 08:55.869
down to about an even
thickness all the way around.

08:55.869 --> 08:57.537
<i>‐ I think my welds are good,</i>

08:57.537 --> 08:59.456
so I'm going to start
turning this into a knife.

08:59.456 --> 09:01.875
This hammer belonged
to my grandfather

09:01.875 --> 09:04.377
who served in World War II.

09:04.377 --> 09:06.212
<i>My blade</i>
<i>is going to be inspired</i>

09:06.212 --> 09:08.715
<i>by those old</i>
<i>'80s action movies.</i>

09:08.715 --> 09:10.675
<i>I'm calling it a</i>
<i>"Get‐To‐Dah‐Choppa"</i>

09:10.675 --> 09:12.052
<i>just 'cause I want to yell</i>

09:12.052 --> 09:13.636
"Get to da choppa!"
in The Forge.

09:13.636 --> 09:15.430
‐ Billy's got a problem.

09:15.430 --> 09:17.640
It looks like that piece
of steel he's working on,

09:17.640 --> 09:19.059
though it's about
3/4 of an inch thick,

09:19.059 --> 09:21.061
is barely six inches long.

09:21.061 --> 09:22.937
Think of that being drawn out,

09:22.937 --> 09:24.606
we're going to have a long,
thin knife over here.

09:24.606 --> 09:26.775
‐ I'm trying to get
my blade shape roughed out

09:26.775 --> 09:29.402
<i>so the billet that I have</i>
<i>looks like my blade</i>

09:29.402 --> 09:31.446
<i>in miniature,</i>
<i>and then as I draw that out</i>

09:31.446 --> 09:33.531
those lines are
going to be accentuated

09:33.531 --> 09:35.283
so that ultimately
my blade just kind of

09:35.283 --> 09:37.911
<i>grows out of the shape</i>
<i>that I've created.</i>

09:37.911 --> 09:40.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:40.955 --> 09:42.624
‐ Shawn's brought
that piece of steel

09:42.624 --> 09:45.335
up to welding temperature
twice now.

09:45.335 --> 09:48.213
I‐I don't know why
he's fluxing again.

09:48.213 --> 09:50.882
‐ When is Shawn going to start
growing out his metal?

09:50.882 --> 09:54.177
‐ With the blade I wanna make,
the focus is ensuring

09:54.177 --> 09:57.931
that I have a nice, thick spine
and I have a nice, deep bevel

09:57.931 --> 09:59.891
<i>that comes all the way up</i>
<i>to the point.</i>

09:59.891 --> 10:01.559
<i>I want to ensure that</i>

10:01.559 --> 10:03.394
<i>when they go</i>
<i>and really abuse that knife</i>

10:03.394 --> 10:07.273
<i>it's actually going</i>
<i>to hold up and not break.</i>

10:07.273 --> 10:09.442
[flames whooshing]

10:09.442 --> 10:14.030
‐ I have to work on getting
a beginning of a tang formed,

10:14.030 --> 10:17.700
<i>and the ends of the mild steel</i>

10:17.700 --> 10:21.454
<i>down by the tang</i>
<i>start delaminating.</i>

10:21.454 --> 10:23.957
I've got problems.

10:26.000 --> 10:29.629
‐ We're seeing some really
dirty welds happening here.

10:29.629 --> 10:32.590
‐ I'm doing nothing but
chasing delaminations

10:32.590 --> 10:34.300
on this blade.

10:34.300 --> 10:35.927
<i>This is FUBAR.</i>

10:35.927 --> 10:38.596
Fouled Up
Beyond All Recognition.

10:38.596 --> 10:41.474
‐ He's got forge scale in it,
it's got gaps in it.

10:41.474 --> 10:44.686
Even if Mike went around
and welded all the way around,

10:44.686 --> 10:46.354
he's still got
all that scale in there

10:46.354 --> 10:47.856
and he's still got
air pockets in there.

10:47.856 --> 10:48.940
‐ Yeah, he's just going
to weld a bubble.

10:48.940 --> 10:50.525
‐ Yeah.

10:50.525 --> 10:52.068
<i>‐ I am totally frustrated</i>
<i>right now.</i>

10:52.068 --> 10:56.114
‐ It's pretty ugly, but...
doing what I can.

10:56.114 --> 10:59.826
But I know I can't quit.
That's not in my nature.

10:59.826 --> 11:01.327
‐ One hour!

11:01.327 --> 11:02.954
You have one hour remaining
in the round!

11:02.954 --> 11:05.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:05.456 --> 11:07.250
The knife I'm making
is a camp knife.

11:07.250 --> 11:10.670
<i>Just an all general</i>
<i>cutter, slasher.</i>

11:10.670 --> 11:12.755
‐ The only problem I have
with Robert right now,

11:12.755 --> 11:14.674
his steel is still thin

11:14.674 --> 11:17.135
and every time he hits
one end it pops up.

11:17.135 --> 11:19.053
‐ Right.

11:19.053 --> 11:21.097
‐ Turns it over to flatten it
out, the other end pops up,

11:21.097 --> 11:23.683
so you just
keep chasing things.

11:23.683 --> 11:25.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:25.602 --> 11:28.229
<i>‐ Everything's looking pretty</i>
<i>good right now.</i>

11:28.229 --> 11:31.024
Of course,
the quench changes everything.

11:31.024 --> 11:35.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.528 --> 11:38.406
‐ All right,
one blade quenched.

11:38.406 --> 11:42.744
‐ I've got a bad bend there.
[groans]

11:42.744 --> 11:44.037
It's got a warp in it.

11:44.037 --> 11:46.164
That is not gonna do it.

11:46.164 --> 11:49.042
I know I need to re‐quench.

11:49.042 --> 11:50.585
Once more.

11:50.585 --> 11:52.253
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:52.253 --> 11:54.214
<i>‐ At this point</i>
<i>I'm feeling great.</i>

11:54.214 --> 11:55.882
I'm feeling like
I produced something

11:55.882 --> 11:57.592
that I'm really happy with.

11:57.592 --> 12:00.220
‐ The cleanest steel
on The Forge floor right now

12:00.220 --> 12:02.805
is coming from the guy
who did the most setup

12:02.805 --> 12:03.890
and that's Shawn.

12:03.890 --> 12:05.433
<i>‐ Once I got my welds set,</i>

12:05.433 --> 12:09.270
I was able to work really,
really fast.

12:09.270 --> 12:11.606
‐ That blade looked hot!

12:11.606 --> 12:13.107
‐ A lot of times a quench

12:13.107 --> 12:15.818
will make that weld pop
or open up.

12:15.818 --> 12:18.780
‐ I come out of the oil
and I'm just super happy.

12:18.780 --> 12:20.406
It looks nice and straight.

12:20.406 --> 12:21.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:21.866 --> 12:23.284
‐ Half an hour!

12:23.284 --> 12:24.702
You've got half an hour
remaining!

12:24.702 --> 12:28.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:28.081 --> 12:30.083
‐ Robert just, uh, quenched.
‐ Yup.

12:30.083 --> 12:34.629
‐ I pull it out and I have
this banana for a blade now.

12:34.629 --> 12:37.715
<i>‐ Robert's got a pretty nasty</i>
<i>warp in that blade, tough.</i>

12:37.715 --> 12:39.133
‐ Go to the vice.

12:39.133 --> 12:41.886
You still got
a couple seconds here.

12:41.886 --> 12:45.098
‐ [groans]
I gotta go back again.

12:45.098 --> 12:50.270
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:50.270 --> 12:52.563
‐ And there's a quench
from Mike.

12:52.563 --> 12:54.607
Sure there's gonna be burning
for a while

12:54.607 --> 12:57.360
'cause there's oil filling up
those delamination pockets.

12:57.360 --> 13:02.073
<i>‐ I can tell that it's hard,</i>
<i>but I notice...</i>

13:02.073 --> 13:05.118
I've got more delaminations.

13:05.118 --> 13:06.869
Oh, boy.
Is that a pop?

13:06.869 --> 13:07.954
‐ Oh, yeah.
‐ Yeah.

13:07.954 --> 13:09.038
‐ It's popping.

13:09.038 --> 13:10.832
‐ You can see on Mike's blade

13:10.832 --> 13:12.834
toward the end, toward the
tang, it's popping up again.

13:12.834 --> 13:15.211
<i>‐ The clock is ticking down.</i>

13:15.211 --> 13:18.006
The only thing that I can do
is hope for the best

13:18.006 --> 13:22.468
and grind out as much of this
as I possibly can.

13:22.468 --> 13:23.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:23.886 --> 13:25.805
<i>‐ The second quench,</i>

13:25.805 --> 13:27.807
<i>I'm a little bit more prepared</i>
<i>this time for a warp.</i>

13:27.807 --> 13:30.518
So it comes out,
it's not warped as bad

13:30.518 --> 13:32.395
<i>but it's still got</i>
<i>a little bit of a warp</i>

13:32.395 --> 13:34.564
<i>so I take my blade,</i>
<i>stick it between the steel‐‐</i>

13:34.564 --> 13:37.150
‐ Stepping down on it.

13:37.150 --> 13:39.986
That's an interesting way
to keep it straight.

13:39.986 --> 13:42.488
<i>‐ There are all kinds of risks</i>
<i>going into the second quench.</i>

13:42.488 --> 13:45.324
I've seen lots and lots
and lots of San Mai blades

13:45.324 --> 13:48.745
<i>develop cracks from going</i>
<i>in their second quench.</i>

13:48.745 --> 13:50.455
<i>‐ Oh, it's way warped.</i>

13:50.455 --> 13:53.207
‐ So, it looks like
Robert and Billy there

13:53.207 --> 13:55.084
dealing with a little bit
of a warp.

13:55.084 --> 13:57.879
<i>‐ This is not really an easy</i>
<i>problem to correct.</i>

13:57.879 --> 13:59.464
It can be fixed,

13:59.464 --> 14:01.174
but I've got to be really,
really careful,

14:01.174 --> 14:03.593
especially right now
because my blade has hardened

14:03.593 --> 14:05.928
and I don't want to break it.

14:05.928 --> 14:07.472
<i>‐ Seemed to get a little bit</i>
<i>of it out</i>

14:07.472 --> 14:09.515
but there's still
quite a bit of a bend in it.

14:09.515 --> 14:11.517
<i>But I don't want</i>
<i>to quench again</i>

14:11.517 --> 14:13.936
<i>because my material is just</i>
<i>completely blowing apart,</i>

14:13.936 --> 14:16.397
so I'm just gonna hope it
carries me on to the next round

14:16.397 --> 14:20.151
and I'll have a chance
to fix it then.

14:20.151 --> 14:25.364
‐ Five, four,
three, two, one...

14:25.364 --> 14:27.241
bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

14:27.241 --> 14:28.618
Stop what you're doing!

14:28.618 --> 14:31.204
This first round
of competition is over.

14:31.204 --> 14:34.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:34.165 --> 14:36.209
<i>‐ Going into the critique,</i>

14:36.209 --> 14:38.753
<i>I'm afraid that the bend that</i>
<i>I have still left in my blade</i>

14:38.753 --> 14:40.421
<i>will probably send me home.</i>

14:40.421 --> 14:42.882
<i>This is not typically</i>
<i>how I like to do‐‐</i>

14:42.882 --> 14:45.384
[chuckles]
how I like do my work.

14:45.384 --> 14:46.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:46.886 --> 14:48.221
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

14:48.221 --> 14:49.889
In this first round
of competition

14:49.889 --> 14:51.307
we asked you guys to forge

14:51.307 --> 14:53.142
signature blades
in your signature style

14:53.142 --> 14:57.605
out of materials harvested
from this Panzer tank.

14:57.605 --> 14:59.065
Now it's time for the judges

14:59.065 --> 15:00.441
to take a closer look
at your work.

15:00.441 --> 15:02.276
Billy, you're up first.

15:02.276 --> 15:04.445
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:04.445 --> 15:06.614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:06.614 --> 15:08.741
<i>‐ Blade's lookin'</i>
<i>pretty solid.</i>

15:08.741 --> 15:11.160
<i>You did a pretty good job</i>
<i>at taking that warp out.</i>

15:11.160 --> 15:14.247
Still there, love to see it
go away completely,

15:14.247 --> 15:17.083
but, uh, good job so far.
‐ Thank you.

15:17.083 --> 15:19.252
‐ All right, Robert.
You're up.

15:19.252 --> 15:22.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:22.171 --> 15:23.756
<i>‐ All right, Robert.</i>

15:23.756 --> 15:25.341
<i>First up, nice shape</i>
<i>that you have here</i>

15:25.341 --> 15:27.093
<i>for chopping, slashing,</i>
<i>and stabbing.</i>

15:27.093 --> 15:29.428
It does have
a very pronounced warp.

15:29.428 --> 15:31.806
And it's already
on the very lean side,

15:31.806 --> 15:33.474
<i>so if you correct this,</i>

15:33.474 --> 15:36.269
make sure that
it doesn't become a very, well,

15:36.269 --> 15:39.522
shall way say,
a very flimsy blade.

15:39.522 --> 15:40.982
‐ All right, Mike.
You're up.

15:40.982 --> 15:42.733
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:42.733 --> 15:44.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:44.902 --> 15:47.488
<i>‐ Well, Mike, you've got a lot</i>
<i>of metal to work with here,</i>

15:47.488 --> 15:50.116
but you got
a lot of issues.

15:50.116 --> 15:52.743
You've got delaminations
up and down the blade

15:52.743 --> 15:54.495
on both sides.

15:54.495 --> 15:57.957
One that really concerns me
is this delamination here,

15:57.957 --> 16:00.334
runs right down the center,

16:00.334 --> 16:02.837
and that's a huge issue
right there.

16:02.837 --> 16:04.463
If you move forward,

16:04.463 --> 16:08.009
I hope you got a plan
for correcting these.

16:08.009 --> 16:09.385
‐ Shawn, you're up next.

16:09.385 --> 16:11.429
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:11.429 --> 16:14.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:14.390 --> 16:18.144
<i>‐ Okay, Shawn,</i>
<i>the steel really looks good.</i>

16:18.144 --> 16:21.105
Big issue is that crack.

16:21.105 --> 16:24.525
That's a clean line right down
the center of that weld.

16:24.525 --> 16:27.904
The color temperature of your
blade when you quenched it,

16:27.904 --> 16:29.322
it was really hot

16:29.322 --> 16:31.908
and that probably
is what popped that weld.

16:31.908 --> 16:33.367
But I like the profile,

16:33.367 --> 16:34.911
I like the weight
of this blade as it is.

16:34.911 --> 16:37.955
So good job on that.
‐ Thank you.

16:37.955 --> 16:39.957
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:39.957 --> 16:41.292
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

16:41.292 --> 16:43.044
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

16:43.044 --> 16:44.587
They've made
their final decision.

16:44.587 --> 16:47.173
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

16:47.173 --> 16:52.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:52.595 --> 16:53.930
Mike.

16:53.930 --> 16:56.557
Your blade didn't make the cut.

16:56.557 --> 16:58.893
‐ All right, Mike,
one thing I do commend you on‐‐

16:58.893 --> 17:01.520
you didn't stop,
you didn't give up.

17:01.520 --> 17:03.481
But at the end of the day,
you've got delaminations

17:03.481 --> 17:06.442
<i>on the edge, on the bottom,</i>
<i>on the top, on the spine</i>

17:06.442 --> 17:08.194
<i>and on the bevels on the side.</i>

17:08.194 --> 17:12.448
So you've got the most issues
and the most to fix.

17:12.448 --> 17:15.201
‐ Mike, please
surrender your blade.

17:15.201 --> 17:17.578
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:17.578 --> 17:19.789
<i>‐ I feel terrible.</i>

17:19.789 --> 17:22.250
I don't think I proved
what I wanted to

17:22.250 --> 17:24.502
<i>but I proved</i>
<i>that I never quit.</i>

17:24.502 --> 17:26.462
I thoroughly enjoyed
the experience

17:26.462 --> 17:31.217
of getting to challenge myself
with something I had never done

17:31.217 --> 17:34.387
<i>and getting</i>
<i>to honor my father.</i>

17:34.387 --> 17:37.139
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:37.139 --> 17:40.184
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

17:40.184 --> 17:42.311
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

17:42.311 --> 17:43.980
which puts you one step closer

17:43.980 --> 17:45.439
to the title
of "Forged in Fire" champion

17:45.439 --> 17:48.359
and that check for $10,000.

17:48.359 --> 17:50.570
It's time to make those blades
fully functional

17:50.570 --> 17:54.490
by attaching handles to them
and you'll have only two hours

17:54.490 --> 17:56.909
in which to complete
all of your work.

17:56.909 --> 18:00.663
<i>That's two hours to attach</i>
<i>the handle, a guard, a pommel,</i>

18:00.663 --> 18:02.415
and address any flaws or issues

18:02.415 --> 18:03.958
that were identified
in round one.

18:03.958 --> 18:05.751
After that,
we're going to test your blades

18:05.751 --> 18:08.588
for strength and durability
in a German helmet chop

18:08.588 --> 18:11.591
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

18:11.591 --> 18:14.343
Good luck, gentlemen.
Your two hours starts...

18:14.343 --> 18:16.345
now.

18:16.345 --> 18:19.015
Run, [bleep]damn it!
[laughter]

18:19.015 --> 18:20.600
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:20.600 --> 18:24.353
‐ Man, guards, pommels,
fixing flaws, two hours.

18:24.353 --> 18:25.938
‐ I hope they have a plan.

18:25.938 --> 18:27.982
I mean, if they've got a plan,
work the plan.

18:27.982 --> 18:29.358
They should be okay.

18:29.358 --> 18:31.193
‐ That'll do.

18:31.193 --> 18:33.112
<i>The first thing that</i>
<i>I'm working on is the guard.</i>

18:33.112 --> 18:37.450
Yes, my blade has some issues
but ultimately this challenge

18:37.450 --> 18:40.536
is to put a handle on
with a guard and a pommel.

18:40.536 --> 18:43.289
‐ The only problem with going
to the guard and handle first

18:43.289 --> 18:46.667
is each one of these issues
takes heat to correct

18:46.667 --> 18:48.252
and if you've got glue
on that blade,

18:48.252 --> 18:51.547
you can get double trouble.

18:51.547 --> 18:54.967
<i>‐ Start peeling away</i>
<i>at that delam on the spine.</i>

18:54.967 --> 18:57.470
‐ The biggest concern I have
with Shawn's blade

18:57.470 --> 18:59.388
is if he starts grinding
that edge

18:59.388 --> 19:02.308
and finds out that that fissure
goes all the way through.

19:02.308 --> 19:04.226
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:04.226 --> 19:07.980
‐ Hopefully I can address the
strength issue in the spine.

19:07.980 --> 19:10.733
<i>If I leave it unattended,</i>

19:10.733 --> 19:12.818
<i>that could split wide open</i>
<i>and blow up.</i>

19:12.818 --> 19:16.030
‐ By laying a bead
on the spine of the blade

19:16.030 --> 19:18.866
to close the crack,
wouldn't Shawn also

19:18.866 --> 19:20.660
be blue backing that blade?
‐ Yes.

19:20.660 --> 19:22.995
<i>‐ Everything's</i>
<i>looking pretty good.</i>

19:22.995 --> 19:25.498
It's time to really go after
this guard and this pommel.

19:25.498 --> 19:27.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:27.833 --> 19:30.961
<i>‐ There is a significant warp</i>
<i>in my blade.</i>

19:30.961 --> 19:32.588
You could see it
from a mile away.

19:32.588 --> 19:34.840
<i>I have to fix this.</i>

19:34.840 --> 19:37.093
‐ One of the advantages
of having that mild steel

19:37.093 --> 19:38.511
on the spine of the blade

19:38.511 --> 19:40.262
is you can flex 'em
quite a bit

19:40.262 --> 19:43.516
and have that mild steel
pick up that warp a little.

19:43.516 --> 19:46.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:46.352 --> 19:50.523
‐ I find a piece of stabilized
hybrid resin for my handle.

19:50.523 --> 19:52.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:52.483 --> 19:55.569
I look at the piece of brass
that I've grabbed for a pommel.

19:55.569 --> 19:59.448
I definitely don't have enough
tang to go and peen it over.

19:59.448 --> 20:02.535
I can either trim down
the length of my handle

20:02.535 --> 20:05.413
<i>or I can go</i>
<i>and extend my tang</i>

20:05.413 --> 20:07.039
<i>with a little bit</i>
<i>of all thread.</i>

20:07.039 --> 20:09.125
I don't want to trim down
my handle.

20:09.125 --> 20:12.128
I feel like it's the right size
for a user's hand

20:12.128 --> 20:15.172
so I decide to weld on
some all thread

20:15.172 --> 20:17.383
and screw the whole handle
together.

20:17.383 --> 20:20.428
‐ So, Shawn's looking
for all thread in the pantry.

20:20.428 --> 20:22.471
That's a good idea.

20:22.471 --> 20:24.724
‐ But, I'm digging around
in everything.

20:24.724 --> 20:26.726
I just can't seem
to find the all thread.

20:26.726 --> 20:28.477
‐ One hour has elapsed!

20:28.477 --> 20:31.689
You have 60 minutes remaining
to finish your blades!

20:31.689 --> 20:33.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:33.315 --> 20:36.235
‐ Uh, come on, Shawn.
Still lookin'.

20:36.235 --> 20:38.279
‐ Is it right
in front of my face?

20:38.279 --> 20:41.240
It's‐‐
I feel so dumb right now.

20:41.240 --> 20:43.200
‐ I spy with my little eye...

20:43.200 --> 20:44.326
‐ Jeez!

20:44.326 --> 20:46.495
I'm just wasting all this time.

20:46.495 --> 20:47.955
<i>I need</i>
<i>to get this pommel on</i>

20:47.955 --> 20:49.582
<i>and make sure</i>
<i>I hit parameters.</i>

20:49.582 --> 20:51.167
‐ I think Shawn's head
is about to explode.

20:51.167 --> 20:55.045
‐ Really?
You kidding me?

20:55.045 --> 20:57.882
Set my hand down and I'm right
on top of the all thread.

20:57.882 --> 21:00.843
Only wasted a bunch of time
doing it, too!

21:01.886 --> 21:04.263
<i>‐ I chose a piece</i>
<i>of birdseye maple</i>

21:04.263 --> 21:06.015
for my main handle material.

21:06.015 --> 21:08.225
<i>I fit it up to my knife,</i>

21:08.225 --> 21:10.603
make a mark about where
I think it needs to be cut,

21:10.603 --> 21:12.938
and I chop
the excess material off.

21:12.938 --> 21:16.442
<i>I go try to fit it up</i>
<i>on my knife and it's short.</i>

21:16.442 --> 21:18.152
[bleep].

21:18.152 --> 21:20.863
I'm probably about
a quarter inch, 3/8ths short.

21:20.863 --> 21:22.782
It's not gonna work.

21:22.782 --> 21:25.743
I have to give the judges
a good, comfortable handle.

21:27.912 --> 21:31.332
I'm up against the clock,
but there's no quit in me.

21:31.332 --> 21:35.127
I happen to find another exact
same piece of birdseye maple.

21:35.127 --> 21:36.545
And here we go.

21:36.545 --> 21:39.715
‐ He's got a nice piece
of natural wood,

21:39.715 --> 21:41.509
but it's not very big.

21:41.509 --> 21:43.052
‐ Okay?
‐ So I'm afraid he's either

21:43.052 --> 21:46.180
going to give us
a short blocky handle

21:46.180 --> 21:48.349
or he's gonna
start thinning that tang out.

21:48.349 --> 21:50.935
That can ruin the structural
integrity of the handle.

21:50.935 --> 21:53.979
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:53.979 --> 21:55.856
‐ Whoo!

21:55.856 --> 21:57.441
‐ I kind of like
what Billy's got going

21:57.441 --> 21:59.985
with the multilayered
handle construction.

21:59.985 --> 22:02.863
‐ I'm going for red, white,
and blue on my handle.

22:02.863 --> 22:05.407
Go America!

22:05.407 --> 22:07.952
My handle's glued up.
There's no time to waste.

22:07.952 --> 22:10.579
<i>I'm shaving the handle</i>
<i>and I blow through</i>

22:10.579 --> 22:12.665
the bottom of the handle a
little bit right into my tang.

22:12.665 --> 22:14.333
<i>If I had another hour,</i>

22:14.333 --> 22:17.169
I'd fix this blow through
but I'm running out of time.

22:17.169 --> 22:19.255
<i>So I try to knock off</i>
<i>all the hot spots</i>

22:19.255 --> 22:20.506
that may bite
into the judge's hands.

22:20.506 --> 22:22.007
I hope I didn't miss anything,

22:22.007 --> 22:24.552
but it's always a gamble
on "Forged in Fire."

22:24.552 --> 22:28.305
‐ 30 minutes remaining
until we test your blades!

22:28.305 --> 22:30.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:30.432 --> 22:32.601
‐ I'm thinking about
what the challenges are.

22:32.601 --> 22:34.478
<i>Your blade</i>
<i>has to be stout enough</i>

22:34.478 --> 22:36.772
<i>to not take a wrinkle</i>
<i>or not to shred</i>

22:36.772 --> 22:38.899
whenever they beat it up
against a steel helmet,

22:38.899 --> 22:40.943
but it also has to be
sharp enough

22:40.943 --> 22:42.695
<i>to be able to cut</i>
<i>a free‐hanging rope.</i>

22:42.695 --> 22:44.196
That's not an easy task to do.

22:44.196 --> 22:46.740
<i>I'm puttin'</i>
<i>a convex edge on it.</i>

22:46.740 --> 22:48.534
<i>I think it'll hold up</i>
<i>to the test</i>

22:48.534 --> 22:50.953
<i>of smashing into a helmet,</i>
<i>but at the same time</i>

22:50.953 --> 22:53.205
be sharp enough
to cut through the rope.

22:53.205 --> 22:55.791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:55.791 --> 22:57.751
<i>‐ The last few minutes</i>
<i>of the round,</i>

22:57.751 --> 23:01.046
I'm running around with this
giant contraption in my hands.

23:01.046 --> 23:03.549
<i>I've got a warp</i>
<i>to straighten out.</i>

23:03.549 --> 23:06.552
I didn't forget!
‐ [laughs]

23:06.552 --> 23:09.138
<i>‐ I got two‐thirds</i>
<i>of the bend out in round one.</i>

23:09.138 --> 23:10.723
I wanna see if I can get
the other third of the way

23:10.723 --> 23:11.724
with the striking jig.

23:11.724 --> 23:13.142
‐ So right here,

23:13.142 --> 23:14.768
with 10 1/2 minutes
left on the clock,

23:14.768 --> 23:16.770
Billy's trying
to blue back his spine

23:16.770 --> 23:18.898
and straighten his blade out
a little bit more.

23:18.898 --> 23:20.983
<i>‐ By clamping up my blade</i>

23:20.983 --> 23:23.485
<i>inside these two pieces</i>
<i>of square stock,</i>

23:23.485 --> 23:27.072
it actually holds the heat away
from the edge of my blade

23:27.072 --> 23:30.409
<i>so I don't have to worry as</i>
<i>much about losing the temper.</i>

23:30.409 --> 23:32.494
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:32.494 --> 23:34.079
Little better.

23:34.079 --> 23:35.331
It's not the prettiest knife
I've ever made,

23:35.331 --> 23:36.582
but it will
get the job done.

23:36.582 --> 23:38.042
This is too much fun.

23:38.042 --> 23:39.793
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

23:39.793 --> 23:41.545
‐ I am so far behind right now.

23:41.545 --> 23:43.547
Now that I've got
my all thread on,

23:43.547 --> 23:46.300
I've got to tap that pommel and
thread the inside of the pommel

23:46.300 --> 23:49.553
so I can screw it on
to the back of the knife.

23:49.553 --> 23:51.347
‐ He's still got to get that

23:51.347 --> 23:54.808
all fit up, glued up,
and shaped.

23:54.808 --> 23:56.435
‐ Let's try that one.

23:56.435 --> 23:59.855
Holy crap.
It actually‐‐it threaded!

23:59.855 --> 24:01.315
Finally I get it fit up,

24:01.315 --> 24:03.150
get everything
screwed together

24:03.150 --> 24:04.818
<i>and I'm just gonna hog</i>
<i>the material off this thing</i>

24:04.818 --> 24:06.779
and get it shaped up
as quickly as possible.

24:06.779 --> 24:08.364
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:08.364 --> 24:13.452
‐ Five, four, three,
two, one...

24:13.452 --> 24:15.204
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

24:15.204 --> 24:16.705
Drop your tools!

24:16.705 --> 24:19.333
This second round
of competition is over!

24:19.333 --> 24:20.876
[applause]

24:20.876 --> 24:22.795
<i>‐ I wish I had</i>
<i>another 20 minutes.</i>

24:22.795 --> 24:24.505
<i>I wish I had a lot</i>
<i>of time back</i>

24:24.505 --> 24:27.508
that I wasted running around
looking for materials,

24:27.508 --> 24:29.051
<i>but as it stands,</i>

24:29.051 --> 24:32.888
I made something
that I think can hold up.

24:32.888 --> 24:34.974
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

24:34.974 --> 24:36.976
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test,

24:36.976 --> 24:39.603
the helmet bash‐and‐slash.

24:39.603 --> 24:41.355
What I'm gonna do
is test the overall strength

24:41.355 --> 24:42.982
of your blade, handle, pommel,

24:42.982 --> 24:45.317
by bashing repeatedly
and brutally

24:45.317 --> 24:47.152
into these World War II
German helmets.

24:47.152 --> 24:48.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:48.737 --> 24:51.532
Billy, you get the first honor.
How you feeling?

24:51.532 --> 24:53.701
‐ Get to the choppin'.
‐ All right, let's do it.

24:53.701 --> 24:55.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:55.744 --> 24:58.872
<i>‐ My heart</i>
<i>is beating out of my chest.</i>

24:58.872 --> 25:00.499
<i>He's gonna</i>
<i>bang it into a helmet,</i>

25:00.499 --> 25:02.584
<i>then he's going</i>
<i>to chop it into a helmet.</i>

25:02.584 --> 25:05.295
Is there gonna be a knife left
when he gets done with this?

25:05.295 --> 25:08.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:08.841 --> 25:11.802
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:11.802 --> 25:18.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:20.561 --> 25:23.355
‐ [laughs]

25:23.355 --> 25:25.691
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:25.691 --> 25:27.568
‐ Blade held up
really well.

25:27.568 --> 25:29.278
Your edge is still good.

25:29.278 --> 25:32.322
Biggest problem I have
is the handle construction.

25:32.322 --> 25:33.866
Having this void back here,

25:33.866 --> 25:36.702
I could definitely cut my hand,
my fingers.

25:36.702 --> 25:40.122
That being said, it held up.
It's still sharp.

25:40.122 --> 25:43.625
Good job.
‐ Thank you.

25:43.625 --> 25:45.377
‐ [chuckles]

25:45.377 --> 25:46.879
It's always worse
for the second guy.

25:46.879 --> 25:48.964
‐ [chuckles]
I'm ready.

25:48.964 --> 25:50.049
‐ All right, let's do it.

25:50.049 --> 25:52.676
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:52.676 --> 25:54.553
<i>‐ I'm certainly nervous.</i>

25:54.553 --> 25:57.139
<i>Anytime you put steel on steel</i>
<i>something's gotta give,</i>

25:57.139 --> 26:00.142
<i>and this helmet,</i>
<i>it's made to deflect bullets.</i>

26:00.142 --> 26:03.312
Who knows what it's gonna do
to my blade?

26:03.312 --> 26:05.439
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:05.439 --> 26:09.610
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

26:09.610 --> 26:16.575
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:19.244 --> 26:21.872
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:21.872 --> 26:24.750
‐ All right, Robert.
Overall, you held up.

26:24.750 --> 26:26.251
But you've got some chipping...

26:26.251 --> 26:28.128
right in here, here, here.

26:28.128 --> 26:29.671
Biggest problem I have
is the handle.

26:29.671 --> 26:31.632
It's very small
and there wasn't enough

26:31.632 --> 26:34.343
to stop my hand
from smacking into the helmet.

26:34.343 --> 26:37.012
So your pommel
didn't take much damage

26:37.012 --> 26:39.598
because my hand
took most of the impact on it.

26:39.598 --> 26:41.183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:41.183 --> 26:43.769
You ready, Shawn?
‐ [chuckles] Not at all.

26:43.769 --> 26:46.146
‐ We're gonna do it anyway.

26:46.146 --> 26:49.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:49.900 --> 26:51.193
<i>‐ J. picks up my blade,</i>

26:51.193 --> 26:52.945
<i>immediately starts shaking it.</i>

26:52.945 --> 26:54.905
<i>Immediately starts</i>
<i>inspecting it,</i>

26:54.905 --> 26:57.157
<i>and I'm just thinking,</i>

26:57.157 --> 26:59.201
<i>"There's no way</i>
<i>he's even going to test this."</i>

26:59.201 --> 27:01.203
<i>When I was shaping my handle,</i>

27:01.203 --> 27:03.455
<i>I was rushing through</i>
<i>and fighting the clock</i>

27:03.455 --> 27:06.416
<i>and just compromised</i>
<i>the structure of that handle.</i>

27:08.585 --> 27:11.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:11.630 --> 27:14.007
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

27:14.007 --> 27:17.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:21.181 --> 27:24.017
‐ That's‐‐it's a‐‐
it's a few pieces.

27:24.017 --> 27:26.812
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:26.812 --> 27:28.647
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:28.647 --> 27:30.148
[sighs]

27:30.148 --> 27:32.234
Well, Shawn,
we got a problem.

27:32.234 --> 27:35.237
‐ We do.
‐ You had voids on both sides.

27:35.237 --> 27:37.364
Your handle was loose.

27:37.364 --> 27:39.700
On the plus side
it's now tight,

27:39.700 --> 27:42.327
because your handle's
popped off at an angle.

27:42.327 --> 27:43.745
It's not in alignment anymore,

27:43.745 --> 27:46.039
and I just don't
have confidence

27:46.039 --> 27:47.666
this is gonna
stay together.

27:47.666 --> 27:49.918
I'm very uncomfortable
with the fact

27:49.918 --> 27:52.296
this thing's gonna
blow apart in my hand.

27:52.296 --> 27:57.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:57.718 --> 28:00.929
‐ Bladesmiths, our weapons
testing is intentionally brutal

28:00.929 --> 28:03.181
to set your weapons
apart from one another

28:03.181 --> 28:05.517
if all the standards are met.

28:05.517 --> 28:07.227
Shawn, unfortunately,

28:07.227 --> 28:09.855
your weapon has been given
a vote of no confidence

28:09.855 --> 28:12.441
and cannot move forward
in testing

28:12.441 --> 28:15.152
and therefore you cannot move
forward in this competition.

28:15.152 --> 28:18.530
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:18.530 --> 28:20.198
‐ Thanks for this opportunity,
I appreciate it.

28:20.198 --> 28:22.242
‐ Thank you, it was great.
You did a good job.

28:22.242 --> 28:24.870
<i>‐ This is one of the greatest</i>
<i>opportunities and experiences</i>

28:24.870 --> 28:27.831
that I've had
making knives in my life.

28:27.831 --> 28:31.376
<i>I will take this and it will</i>
<i>be a lasting memory forever.</i>

28:31.376 --> 28:33.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:33.670 --> 28:36.048
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:36.048 --> 28:37.841
‐ Billy, Robert,
congratulations.

28:37.841 --> 28:40.218
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

28:40.218 --> 28:42.971
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:42.971 --> 28:46.975
to recreate an iconic weapon
that helped win World War II.

28:46.975 --> 28:49.937
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

28:49.937 --> 28:51.563
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:51.563 --> 28:55.067
The Scottish backsword.

28:55.067 --> 28:57.945
<i>Known for assaulting</i>
<i>Axis positions</i>

28:57.945 --> 28:59.947
<i>with his</i>
<i>Scottish backsword drawn,</i>

28:59.947 --> 29:01.990
<i>"Mad Jack" Churchill</i>
<i>earned his name</i>

29:01.990 --> 29:03.742
<i>and the respect of his troops</i>

29:03.742 --> 29:05.953
<i>for his famed exploits</i>
<i>during World War II.</i>

29:05.953 --> 29:07.704
<i>The backsword</i>
<i>first came of fashion</i>

29:07.704 --> 29:10.040
<i>during the 16th century</i>
<i>and is recognized</i>

29:10.040 --> 29:12.793
<i>for its basket hilt</i>
<i>that covers the user's hand,</i>

29:12.793 --> 29:14.962
<i>offering complete protection.</i>

29:14.962 --> 29:16.922
<i>Featuring a straight</i>
<i>and lethal single edge,</i>

29:16.922 --> 29:19.049
<i>the weapon was a brutal</i>
<i>slicer and thruster</i>

29:19.049 --> 29:22.636
<i>on the battlefield, especially</i>
<i>when wielded by "Mad Jack."</i>

29:22.636 --> 29:24.513
<i>A true wartime hero,</i>

29:24.513 --> 29:26.473
<i>"Mad Jack" eventually served</i>
<i>as a commando leader</i>

29:26.473 --> 29:29.643
<i>helping Allied forces</i>
<i>save Europe from destruction.</i>

29:29.643 --> 29:32.729
Make it beautiful,
make it your own,

29:32.729 --> 29:35.774
just make sure it falls within
the following parameters.

29:35.774 --> 29:39.152
It must have a fuller
that favors the spine,

29:39.152 --> 29:41.530
a false edge,
and a basket hilt

29:41.530 --> 29:43.615
that encompasses
the entire hand

29:43.615 --> 29:46.660
and includes
the guard handle and pommel.

29:46.660 --> 29:48.370
<i>‐ A Scottish what?</i>

29:48.370 --> 29:49.788
I‐I have no idea.

29:49.788 --> 29:51.498
I've never even heard
of this thing.

29:51.498 --> 29:53.667
<i>I mean, I've made one</i>
<i>basket hilt before,</i>

29:53.667 --> 29:56.294
but it was nothing like this.

29:56.294 --> 29:57.671
‐ You have four days
at your home forges

29:57.671 --> 29:59.297
in which to complete
this challenge.

29:59.297 --> 30:01.341
At the end of those four days
you'll return

30:01.341 --> 30:04.219
and present your swords
to our panel of expert judges.

30:04.219 --> 30:06.013
And after they
put 'em through the paces,

30:06.013 --> 30:08.515
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:08.515 --> 30:11.601
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

30:11.601 --> 30:14.896
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

30:14.896 --> 30:17.858
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

30:17.858 --> 30:20.193
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:20.193 --> 30:22.988
<i>‐ So, it's day one</i>
<i>and I'm going to get started</i>

30:22.988 --> 30:24.448
on my Scottish backsword.

30:24.448 --> 30:26.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:26.491 --> 30:29.244
So right now
I'm just cleaning off my steel

30:29.244 --> 30:31.997
<i>just to make sure that</i>
<i>I get a good clean forge weld.</i>

30:31.997 --> 30:34.708
I don't have the steel
that's the proper thickness

30:34.708 --> 30:36.251
so I'm gonna be forge welding

30:36.251 --> 30:37.919
<i>three pieces</i>
<i>of 1080 steel together.</i>

30:37.919 --> 30:39.463
<i>I'm doing it all by hand</i>

30:39.463 --> 30:40.881
so it's going to take
a little bit longer.

30:40.881 --> 30:46.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:46.928 --> 30:51.266
‐ So I'm making
a Scottish backsword.

30:51.266 --> 30:52.726
<i>I'm gonna try to make it</i>

30:52.726 --> 30:55.812
as historically accurate
as I possibly can.

30:55.812 --> 30:57.147
Let's make it hot!

30:57.147 --> 30:58.774
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:58.774 --> 31:00.567
<i>Day one</i>
<i>is making the Damascus,</i>

31:00.567 --> 31:03.195
<i>forging the blade,</i>
<i>and then quench.</i>

31:03.195 --> 31:05.155
Whoo, boy!

31:05.155 --> 31:07.115
<i>There's a risk that</i>
<i>the Damascus will blow apart</i>

31:07.115 --> 31:08.617
<i>and if it messes up</i>

31:08.617 --> 31:11.286
I won't have time
to start again.

31:11.286 --> 31:14.081
<i>Forge welding Damascus</i>
<i>is always a risky thing.</i>

31:14.081 --> 31:16.792
It'll make the blade far
more aesthetically pleasing,

31:16.792 --> 31:21.046
<i>which will hopefully give me</i>
<i>a boost in this competition.</i>

31:21.046 --> 31:22.464
<i>Things are okay.</i>

31:22.464 --> 31:23.757
<i>I've got my blade</i>
<i>forged to shape.</i>

31:23.757 --> 31:26.134
I'm ready to go in the quench.

31:26.134 --> 31:30.055
I can't believe I
got this much done in one day.

31:30.055 --> 31:32.265
♪ ♪

31:32.265 --> 31:35.644
I think that might've
been a successful quench.

31:35.644 --> 31:37.270
Coming out...

31:37.270 --> 31:38.271
[chuckles]

31:38.271 --> 31:40.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:40.565 --> 31:43.068
<i>So, today I have a little bit</i>
<i>of grinding left</i>

31:43.068 --> 31:45.403
<i>to establish my bevels.</i>

31:45.403 --> 31:47.739
And then the plan after that
is heat treat.

31:47.739 --> 31:49.449
Once I come
right out of the quench,

31:49.449 --> 31:53.078
lay the sword down here,
clamp everything down tight,

31:53.078 --> 31:55.080
and hopefully
if there is any warp

31:55.080 --> 31:58.291
it straightens it out
as the blade is cooling.

31:58.291 --> 32:02.170
If things go wrong here I could
possibly have to start over.

32:05.132 --> 32:07.467
<i>I have to nail it and</i>
<i>get it right the first time.</i>

32:07.467 --> 32:09.427
All right, here we go.

32:09.427 --> 32:12.472
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:12.472 --> 32:15.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:15.684 --> 32:18.311
<i>I saw some good color when</i>
<i>it come out of the quench.</i>

32:18.311 --> 32:19.855
<i>The blade looked</i>
<i>fairly straight.</i>

32:19.855 --> 32:21.565
I didn't hear
any tinks or cracks

32:21.565 --> 32:23.817
or anything happen
so I think we're good.

32:23.817 --> 32:26.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:26.319 --> 32:29.906
‐ My plan for today
is make the basket hilt.

32:29.906 --> 32:32.826
<i>It's easily the toughest part</i>
<i>of this build.</i>

32:32.826 --> 32:34.870
<i>I'm gonna try my best</i>
<i>to make this thing</i>

32:34.870 --> 32:37.289
<i>out a single piece of steel.</i>

32:37.289 --> 32:40.542
And that's why
you drill it slow.

32:40.542 --> 32:42.752
<i>I'm gonna try</i>
<i>to put my own spin on it.</i>

32:42.752 --> 32:44.462
<i>I wanna put an American flag</i>

32:44.462 --> 32:47.090
<i>and the shape</i>
<i>of the Purple Heart Medal</i>

32:47.090 --> 32:50.051
to honor the men and women who
have given all to our country.

32:50.051 --> 32:52.179
At least as much as work's
going into the handle

32:52.179 --> 32:54.639
as is going into the blade.

32:54.639 --> 33:00.145
It can be a Scottish backsword
with an American touch.

33:00.145 --> 33:04.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:04.024 --> 33:06.902
‐ Today my main focus
is gonna be on the hilt.

33:06.902 --> 33:10.197
<i>To get this hilt going</i>
<i>what I'm going to need to do</i>

33:10.197 --> 33:14.034
is tack the guard and quillions
to the blade itself

33:14.034 --> 33:18.580
<i>in order to start building</i>
<i>the basket around that.</i>

33:18.580 --> 33:22.042
<i>I'm very happy</i>
<i>with my progress so far.</i>

33:22.042 --> 33:24.628
I feel like I have
a real good shot.

33:24.628 --> 33:25.921
<i>Hopefully it holds up</i>

33:25.921 --> 33:28.882
to whatever test
they throw at me.

33:28.882 --> 33:30.175
‐ [whimpers]

33:30.175 --> 33:32.469
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:32.469 --> 33:35.931
<i>‐ Everything looks great,</i>
<i>but I've got one final touch</i>

33:35.931 --> 33:37.682
<i>that I want to do</i>
<i>to my weapon.</i>

33:37.682 --> 33:39.059
I'll use a little purple,

33:39.059 --> 33:40.936
a little gold,
and a little silver

33:40.936 --> 33:44.564
<i>and I really brighten up</i>
<i>the image of the Purple Heart.</i>

33:44.564 --> 33:47.609
She is a beautiful,
beautiful sword.

33:47.609 --> 33:49.069
<i>What can I test it on?</i>

33:49.069 --> 33:51.446
<i>I wanna be the first person</i>

33:51.446 --> 33:52.906
<i>to hack something up</i>
<i>with this thing.</i>

33:52.906 --> 33:56.076
It just screams,
"Go out and swing me!"

33:56.076 --> 33:59.913
But I'm not putting my blade
through a rigorous test, here.

33:59.913 --> 34:01.581
I'm just seeing
if the edge is good...

34:01.581 --> 34:03.750
<i>so I set up</i>
<i>some swim noodles.</i>

34:03.750 --> 34:05.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:05.752 --> 34:08.088
That'll do.

34:09.422 --> 34:12.425
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

34:12.425 --> 34:15.011
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:15.011 --> 34:18.348
‐ Billy, Robert,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:18.348 --> 34:20.934
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges

34:20.934 --> 34:23.561
to work on your
Scottish backswords.

34:23.561 --> 34:25.939
Billy, tell us
about your blade.

34:25.939 --> 34:27.440
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:27.440 --> 34:29.484
<i>‐ My blade is</i>
<i>46 layer Damascus.</i>

34:29.484 --> 34:31.569
<i>The handle</i>
<i>is African blackwood</i>

34:31.569 --> 34:33.863
<i>with a twisted wire inlay</i>

34:33.863 --> 34:37.033
<i>and the guard</i>
<i>is a solid piece of mild steel</i>

34:37.033 --> 34:40.203
<i>with a purple heart etched</i>
<i>into it to honor our troops.</i>

34:40.203 --> 34:41.997
‐ Nice, nice.

34:41.997 --> 34:44.249
All right, Robert.
What have you got?

34:44.249 --> 34:47.794
<i>‐ I used three layers</i>
<i>of 1080 steel</i>

34:47.794 --> 34:49.754
<i>and forge welded together.</i>

34:49.754 --> 34:51.715
<i>Mild steel</i>
<i>for the basket hilt,</i>

34:51.715 --> 34:55.093
<i>and a trailer ball</i>
<i>for my pommel.</i>

34:55.093 --> 34:56.511
‐ All right, gentlemen.

34:56.511 --> 34:57.887
Your weapons
will now be put through

34:57.887 --> 34:59.472
a series of three tests.

34:59.472 --> 35:01.141
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:01.141 --> 35:02.976
and up first, the KEAL test.

35:02.976 --> 35:03.977
Doug?

35:03.977 --> 35:06.771
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:06.771 --> 35:08.398
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

35:08.398 --> 35:10.984
Captain "Mad Jack" Churchill
may have been mad enough

35:10.984 --> 35:13.403
to take a backsword
into modern combat.

35:13.403 --> 35:15.030
But what I want to know is,

35:15.030 --> 35:19.951
are your swords mad enough
if called upon to KEAL?

35:19.951 --> 35:21.453
To that end,
I will deliver

35:21.453 --> 35:23.955
some killing blows
to this ballistics dummy.

35:23.955 --> 35:25.749
Billy, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:25.749 --> 35:27.751
‐ I came here to watch you kill
and chew bubble gum,

35:27.751 --> 35:30.587
and I'm out of bubble gum.
‐ [chuckles] All right!

35:30.587 --> 35:33.006
Let's do this!

35:33.006 --> 35:34.382
<i>‐ There are a number</i>
<i>of things that could go wrong</i>

35:34.382 --> 35:36.134
<i>in this kind of test.</i>

35:36.134 --> 35:38.970
If my blade gets twisted wrong,
maybe it breaks it.

35:38.970 --> 35:43.183
I‐I don't know, I've never
chopped into a torso before.

35:43.183 --> 35:46.186
<i>[exciting music]</i>

35:46.186 --> 35:52.817
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:07.248 --> 36:08.375
[wet thud]

36:08.375 --> 36:10.752
[laughter]

36:10.752 --> 36:13.755
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

36:13.755 --> 36:16.716
‐ All right, Billy,
first off, I really like

36:16.716 --> 36:20.053
the way the Damascus pattern
shows in your sword.

36:20.053 --> 36:23.431
Now, your handle...
it's comfortable.

36:23.431 --> 36:25.141
There are no hot spots.

36:25.141 --> 36:27.227
Every cut you do
with this blade

36:27.227 --> 36:29.938
is sharp enough to cut deeply.

36:29.938 --> 36:33.274
Overall, your weapon will KEAL.

36:33.274 --> 36:35.485
‐ Thank you very much.

36:35.485 --> 36:36.778
‐ All right, Robert.
Your turn, sir.

36:36.778 --> 36:38.113
Are you ready?
‐ I'm ready.

36:38.113 --> 36:40.865
‐ Let's do this.

36:40.865 --> 36:44.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:44.869 --> 36:47.914
<i>[exciting music]</i>

36:47.914 --> 36:54.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:07.767 --> 37:09.936
[laughter]

37:11.396 --> 37:14.607
I will not be denied.
[laughter]

37:14.607 --> 37:16.568
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

37:16.568 --> 37:17.902
All right, Robert.

37:17.902 --> 37:19.654
Let's talk about
your backsword here.

37:19.654 --> 37:21.322
The tip, very pointy.

37:21.322 --> 37:25.076
Thrust in easily.
Cuts on the way out.

37:25.076 --> 37:26.703
Your handle here, it's loose.

37:26.703 --> 37:28.747
It's really wiggling
in my hand.

37:28.747 --> 37:32.876
But overall, sir,
your backsword will KEAL.

37:32.876 --> 37:34.753
‐ Thank you.

37:37.088 --> 37:40.467
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

37:40.467 --> 37:42.385
Today I'm going to take
your swords

37:42.385 --> 37:45.221
and I'm going to clear a path
through this big block of ice.

37:45.221 --> 37:47.307
I don't really care
what your swords do to the ice.

37:47.307 --> 37:49.392
I want to see what the ice
does to your swords.

37:49.392 --> 37:51.895
Billy, you look
ready to be first.

37:51.895 --> 37:54.105
‐ J., I was born ready.
‐ There we go.

37:54.105 --> 37:59.194
‐ This is terrifying.
J. has a reputation.

37:59.194 --> 38:03.740
A well‐deserved reputation
for breaking things.

38:03.740 --> 38:08.620
Today I hope not to add my
blade to a long list of victims

38:08.620 --> 38:09.913
<i>that have fallen prey</i>
<i>to J. Neilson.</i>

38:15.627 --> 38:18.421
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

38:18.421 --> 38:25.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:36.815 --> 38:38.775
‐ [chuckles]

38:38.775 --> 38:40.985
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:40.985 --> 38:42.946
‐ Billy, nice job.
‐ Thank you.

38:42.946 --> 38:44.823
‐ I'm sure you could see
when I was striking at‐‐

38:44.823 --> 38:46.991
the blade flexed
all over the place

38:46.991 --> 38:49.327
and came right back to where
it was in the beginning.

38:49.327 --> 38:51.287
Everything's tight.
Nice job.

38:51.287 --> 38:52.956
‐ Thank you very much.

38:52.956 --> 38:54.916
‐ Robert, how you feeling?
‐ I'm ready.

38:54.916 --> 38:56.835
‐ Good, I'm ready too.
Let's do it.

38:56.835 --> 38:59.003
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:59.003 --> 39:01.631
‐ I'd be lying if I said
I'm not nervous right now.

39:01.631 --> 39:03.842
<i>A sword isn't made</i>
<i>to hit a block of ice.</i>

39:03.842 --> 39:06.344
<i>When two hard things</i>
<i>hit each other like that</i>

39:06.344 --> 39:08.179
<i>something's got to give.</i>

39:08.179 --> 39:11.349
Hopefully the ice gives
more than what my sword gives.

39:11.349 --> 39:15.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:15.854 --> 39:18.815
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

39:18.815 --> 39:20.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:20.483 --> 39:23.403
‐ [groans]

39:23.403 --> 39:26.364
[groans]

39:26.364 --> 39:27.866
<i>‐ Oh, no.</i>

39:27.866 --> 39:29.534
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:29.534 --> 39:31.661
<i>I really don't know</i>
<i>what to think right now.</i>

39:31.661 --> 39:33.162
‐ It's right here
is where it hurts.

39:33.162 --> 39:34.789
Feels like something pulled.

39:34.789 --> 39:37.000
‐ Watching J. scream out
in pain like that,

39:37.000 --> 39:38.835
<i>I feel that pain as well.</i>

39:38.835 --> 39:41.713
‐ It's kinda catching me
a little bit back here.

39:41.713 --> 39:43.715
‐ I hate that
something that I did

39:43.715 --> 39:45.300
caused pain to another person.

39:45.300 --> 39:48.344
‐ Plus, it's loose.
[metal clacks]

39:48.344 --> 39:51.681
<i>‐ I see J. stepping off</i>
<i>the testing floor.</i>

39:51.681 --> 39:55.226
I'm pretty sure this is‐‐
this is it‐‐this is it for me.

39:56.519 --> 39:59.230
‐ Bladesmiths, in any one
of our finale competitions

39:59.230 --> 40:01.149
the way that you design
those blades

40:01.149 --> 40:02.567
to perform in our challenges

40:02.567 --> 40:04.569
is always taken
into consideration.

40:04.569 --> 40:06.237
And Robert, unfortunately,

40:06.237 --> 40:09.532
your weapon has hurt our user
so severely

40:09.532 --> 40:11.868
that we had to send him
to the emergency room.

40:11.868 --> 40:14.454
Your weapon has been given
a vote of no confidence

40:14.454 --> 40:16.873
and cannot move forward
in testing,

40:16.873 --> 40:18.416
and for that reason

40:18.416 --> 40:20.543
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

40:20.543 --> 40:23.046
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:23.046 --> 40:25.214
‐ First and foremost,
I hope that J. doesn't suffer

40:25.214 --> 40:27.634
any long‐term effects
of this injury.

40:27.634 --> 40:29.677
<i>I took my time making sure</i>

40:29.677 --> 40:31.095
<i>that everything was safe</i>
<i>on this blade</i>

40:31.095 --> 40:33.765
so to find out
that I missed something

40:33.765 --> 40:36.309
is kind of devastating,
you know?

40:36.309 --> 40:38.061
I know that
I'm able to compete

40:38.061 --> 40:40.605
with some of the best
bladesmiths here in the world.

40:40.605 --> 40:43.274
I know that this is my place,
this is my calling in life.

40:43.274 --> 40:44.776
I'm certainly
not going to stop.

40:44.776 --> 40:46.152
I'm gonna keep pushing forward,

40:46.152 --> 40:47.779
I'm gonna get better
at what I do.

40:47.779 --> 40:52.450
This is just another rung
in the ladder to success.

40:52.450 --> 40:56.454
‐ Billy, your blade is sharp,
deadly, and strong,

40:56.454 --> 40:58.247
and you are
the "Forge of Fire" champion,

40:58.247 --> 41:00.541
and that is a title that
comes with a check for $10,000.

41:00.541 --> 41:02.418
Good job, brother.

41:02.418 --> 41:03.753
<i>‐ Whoo!</i>
<i>[claps]</i>

41:03.753 --> 41:05.797
I'm the
"Forged in Fire" champion!

41:05.797 --> 41:07.632
This is awesome!

41:07.632 --> 41:10.510
<i>This is definitely not the way</i>
<i>that I hoped to win,</i>

41:10.510 --> 41:13.304
but I was given the privilege
of doing this for a day

41:13.304 --> 41:14.973
when I can also honor
those who have given me

41:14.973 --> 41:16.557
<i>the freedom to do this.</i>

41:16.557 --> 41:18.101
<i>This has been</i>
<i>an amazing experience,</i>

41:18.101 --> 41:19.352
and I'm very blessed
and honored

41:19.352 --> 41:21.187
to have been a part of it.

41:21.187 --> 41:25.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>
